ndex=\"0\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-feedback\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-feedback\"></use></svg><span class=\"zDocsFeedbackButtonText\"> Feedback</span></span></div></div><div class=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><button aria-label=\"Show topic actions\" data-toggle=\"dropdown\" id=\"zDocsTopicActionsMobile\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-ellipsis-h\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-ellipsis-h\"></use></svg></button><div class=\"dropdown-menu zDocsDropdownMenu zDocsTopicActionsMobileDropdown dropdown-menu-right\"></div></div><div style=\"flex-basis: 100%; height: 0px;\"></div><ul class=\"zDocsTopicPageDetails\"><li class=\"zDocsTopicPageDate css-cinqea\">Last Updated<span class=\"css-cinqea\">Okt 13, 2022</span></li><li class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryDetailsItem\"><button class=\"zDocsAiTopicSummaryButton\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-topic-summary\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-topic-summary\"></use></svg>Summarize</button></li><li class=\"spacer\" role=\"presentation\"></li><div class=\"zDocsLabelWrapper\"><ul><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: Uniface\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=prod_uniface\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>Uniface</a></li><li class=\"zDocsLabel\"><a aria-describedby=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" class=\"css-ettsdk\" data-tooltip-content=\"Search all site by tag: 10.4\" data-tooltip-id=\"hyperLinkFacetsTooltip\" href=\"/de-DE/search?labelkey=uniface_10.4\" stylesprops=\"[object Object]\"><svg aria-label=\"Tag\" class=\"ico-tag\" role=\"img\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-tag\"></use></svg>10.4</a></li></ul></div></ul></header><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBody\" data-prismjs-copy=\"Copy\" data-prismjs-copy-error=\"Copy failed! Use Ctrl + C instead.\" data-prismjs-copy-success=\"Copied!\"><div class=\"zDocsTopicPageBodyContent wide\" dir=\"ltr\"><div id=\"zDocsAiSummaryContaineruniface_104kjp1665702976153.html\"></div><div><article class=\"hascomments\" data-page=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/kjp1665702976153.html\" id=\"bundle:uniface_104/enus/kjp1665702976153.html\"><main role=\"main\"><article aria-labelledby=\"ariaid-title1\" class=\"dita\" id=\"kjp1665702976153\" role=\"article\">\n<h1 class=\"title topictitle1\" id=\"ariaid-title1\">\n      Database Cursors\n </h1>\n<div class=\"body conbody\" id=\"kjp1665702976153__database_cursors_177972\"><p class=\"shortdesc\">Some DBMSs support a feature called cursors. A database cursor identifies the internal state of execution of a DML statement in the DBMS itself.\n </p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"kjp1665702976153__p_d61937e1_d61938e1_d61939e1\">Cursors are used to associate function calls via the API with a specific DML statement. Cursors also provide a bridge from the record-oriented 3GL programming language to the set-oriented query language.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"kjp1665702976153__p_d61940e1_d61941e1_d61942e1\">The DBMS connector can improve performance by maintaining a cache of cursors. In this way, a recurring query can be executed without being parsed again by the DBMS. A common technique in DBMS connectors for RDBMSs is to associate a standard set of cursors with every open table. By reserving one or more cursors for some connector requests, performance is significantly improved.</p>\n<section class=\"section\" id=\"kjp1665702976153__topic_d40967e1_d40968e1_d40969e1_d40970e1_d40971e1\"><h2 class=\"title sectiontitle\" id=\"d743395e59\">\n                        \n Management of File and Cursor Resources\n </h2>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"kjp1665702976153__p_d61946e1_d61947e1_d61948e1\">Uniface guarantees that no run-time violation will occur on the maximum number of open operating system files and open DBMS cursors. If a maximum would be exceeded by opening a table, Uniface first temporarily closes one or more tables to release resources.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"kjp1665702976153__p_d61949e1_d61950e1_d61951e1\">During the execution of connector requests, the connector can dynamically open and close operating system files and DBMS cursors. The connector must inform Uniface about the number of files and cursors that it has opened or closed by calling the <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"fjd1665702918235.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/fjd1665702918235.html\" title=\"Return the number of open database cursors.\">udcurscnt</a> and <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"prf1665702918304.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/prf1665702918304.html\" title=\"Return the number of open operating system files.\">udfilcnt</a> service functions.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"kjp1665702976153__p_d61952e1_d61953e1_d61954e1\">The connector must inform Uniface about the maximum number of files that it can have open simultaneously for one open table, and about the maximum number of open cursors allowed by the DBMS. See <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"iga1665702915956.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/iga1665702915956.html\" title=\"Supplies Uniface with basic information about the DBMS and the connector.\">uinfo</a> and <a class=\"xref\" data-bundleid=\"uniface_104\" data-navpath=\"azl1665702915888.html\" href=\"/de-DE/bundle/uniface_104/page/azl1665702915888.html\" title=\"Exchanges general information between Uniface and the connector, and describes a table.\">uctrl</a>.</p>\n<p class=\"p\" id=\"kjp1665702976153__p_d61955e1_d61956e1_d61957e1\">If the connector supplies Uniface with correct information as described above, the resource management mechanisms are automatically handled by Uniface.</p>\n</section>\n</div>\n</article></main></article>\n</div></div></div><div class=\"bottomFeedback\"><div aria-labelledby=\"bottomFeedbackText\" class=\"bottomFeedbackContent\" role=\"group\"><span class=\"bottomFeedbackText\" id=\"bottomFeedbackText\">Was this topic helpful?</span><div class=\"bottomFeedbackButtonGroup\"><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2529234\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-up\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-up\"></use></svg><span>Like</span></a><a data-backdrop=\"static\" data-target=\"#feedbackModal_bottom_2529234\" data-toggle=\"modal\" href=\"#\" role=\"button\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-thumbs-down\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-thumbs-down\"></use></svg><span>Dislike</span></a></div></div></div><div style=\"position: fixed; bottom: 170px; right: 70px; cursor: pointer; transition-duration: 0.2s; transition-timing-function: linear; transition-delay: 0s; z-index: 3; opacity: 0; visibility: hidden; transition-property: opacity, visibility;\"><button aria-label=\"Scroll to top\" class=\"zDocsScrollTopBtn\" data-tooltip-content=\"Scroll to top\" data-tooltip-id=\"zDocsBackToTopToolTip\" id=\"zDocsScrollToTop\" type=\"button\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"ico-next\"><use xlink:href=\"#ico-next\"></use></svg></button></div></body></html>", "text": "Database Cursors Add to My Topics Add selected topic and subtopics Add Topic & Subtopics with topic head Add entire publication Watch Download PDF Save selected topic Save selected topic and subtopics Save entire publication Share Email Link Copy Link Feedback Last Updated Okt 13, 2022 Summarize Uniface 10.4 Database Cursors Some DBMSs support a feature called cursors. A database cursor identifies the internal state of execution of a DML statement in the DBMS itself. Cursors are used to associate function calls via the API with a specific DML statement. Cursors also provide a bridge from the record-oriented 3GL programming language to the set-oriented query language. The DBMS connector can improve performance by maintaining a cache of cursors. In this way, a recurring query can be executed without being parsed again by the DBMS. A common technique in DBMS connectors for RDBMSs is to associate a standard set of cursors with every open table. By reserving one or more cursors for some connector requests, performance is significantly improved. Management of File and Cursor Resources Uniface guarantees that no run-time violation will occur on the maximum number of open operating system files and open DBMS cursors. If a maximum would be exceeded by opening a table, Uniface first temporarily closes one or more tables to release resources. During the execution of connector requests, the connector can dynamically open and close operating system files and DBMS cursors. The connector must inform Uniface about the number of files and cursors that it has opened or closed by calling the udcurscnt and udfilcnt service functions. The connector must inform Uniface about the maximum number of files that it can have open simultaneously for one open table, and about the maximum number of open cursors allowed by the DBMS. See uinfo and uctrl . If the connector supplies Uniface with correct information as described above, the resource management mechanisms are automatically handled by Uniface. Was this topic helpful? Like Dislike"}